  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Luma Health Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Luma Health review 2026: patient engagement and scheduling platform features, custom pricing, funding, pros, cons, and alternatives for healthcare teams.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Luma Health is a healthcare technology company founded in 2015 and headquartered in San Mateo, California, that builds an operational patient engagement platform used by hospitals, health systems, and clinics to automate communication and coordination across the patient journey. It is entirely unrelated to two other companies with similar branding: Lu.ma, the general-purpose events and ticketing platform, and Luma AI, the generative video and 3D company behind Dream Machine. Luma Health describes its mission as unifying every step of the patient journey, from initial scheduling through referrals, reminders, check-in, follow-up, and recall, into a single automated communication layer that sits on top of a health system's existing electronic health record and practice management systems rather than replacing them. The company has raised approximately 156 million dollars in disclosed funding, with its most notable round being a 130 million dollar Series C led by FTV Capital, which the company said would be used to scale internationally and expand its operational AI capabilities for healthcare. Luma Health positions its product as operational AI for healthcare, reflecting a shift in its messaging toward automation and AI-assisted workflows for tasks like appointment scheduling, waitlist management, and patient outreach that traditionally required significant manual staff time from front-desk and call-center teams. Architecturally, Luma Health integrates directly with major electronic health record systems to pull and push scheduling, referral, and patient contact data, then layers automated, multi-channel communication, including text messaging, email, and phone, on top of that data to handle tasks such as appointment reminders, digital intake forms, automated waitlist backfill when a slot opens up, referral scheduling, and post-visit follow-up or recall campaigns for preventive care. The platform is built for large, complex healthcare organizations, and its own marketing describes the product as well suited to larger healthcare organizations and multi-location systems with intricate scheduling and integration requirements, rather than small independent practices. Because Luma Health does not publish pricing publicly, prospective customers must go through a sales consultation in which a representative evaluates the size of the practice or health system, existing patient volume, the specific features required, and the complexity of the EHR integration involved before providing a quote; third-party reviews and cost estimate sites have reported anecdotal pricing figures in the range of roughly 250 dollars per user per month, though Luma Health itself does not confirm this publicly, and actual contract pricing likely varies considerably based on organization size and scope. The company's target audience includes hospital systems, multi-specialty clinics, federally qualified health centers, and other healthcare provider organizations seeking to reduce no-show rates, decrease administrative burden on front-office staff, and improve patient access and satisfaction metrics. Luma Health's primary competitors in the patient engagement and scheduling technology space include Solutionreach, NextGen Healthcare's patient engagement tools, Phreesia, Relatient, and Klara, along with broader healthcare CRM and communication platforms. Luma Health differentiates itself through its EHR-agnostic integration approach, meaning it is designed to layer on top of many different underlying EHR systems rather than being tied to one vendor's ecosystem, and through its more recent emphasis on operational AI, positioning automated decision-making and workflow orchestration, rather than simple reminder messaging, as its core value proposition to health system executives evaluating patient access and revenue-cycle technology investments.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'd6bc44bb-56fc-4d52-8fe2-1b741120a0df';

